result.execSummary:
Jason P Sudbeck was extradited to another county, state or jurisdiction. Extradition means Jason P Sudbeck was accused or convicted of an offense in another county, state or jurisdiction and was taken there to face their charge(s) or conviction.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

11:06 AM Prosecuting attorney John Michael O'Boyle in court for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant Jason P Sudbeck appeared by video, in custody.  Attorney Nicholas Von Davis in court for Jason P Sudbeck.
Court relates.  Attorney Davis relates Defendant does not contest extradition.  11:08 Court in recess.  11:12 Waiver of Extradition form provided to Defendant.  Court questions Defendant.  Defendant signs Waiver of Extradition form.  Court finds waiver is knowingly, intelligently and voluntarily given.
Adjourned initial appearance on April 5, 2022 at 11:15 am.; sent to Defendant at BC Jail on 3/17/22

Defendant shall be fingerprinted at the Barron County Sheriff's Dept., if not already done.
If represented by the Public Defender and does not have a phone, must contact the Public Defender weekly at 715-908-8473.

Qualifies for Public Defender and Attorney Nick Davis will likely be appointed. State requests cash bond 1:03 Attorney Knaak and Defendant put in a break out room 1:05 Attorney Knaak requests signature bond 1:06 Court sets cash bond.
